abstract = {Precision medicine is an emerging field to maximize therapeutic benefits by stratifying the treatment of patient groups based on parameters such as demographics and different omics-based molecular profiling data obtained from patient specimens before, during, and after the treatment. Precision medicine may also entail validating population-wide data to develop and validate actionable molecular targets and matching them to available targeted therapies. The process of precision medicine may involve machine learning algorithms and artificial intelligence (AI) to design a drug based on a patient’s data. Unfortunately, not every patient will benefit from a specific precision medicine strategy. Recent evidence indicates that precision medicine is not effective in 93% of patients, mostly due to the pathogenesis of the disease, patient and tumor heterogeneity, the quality and timing of the specimen collection, the stage of the disease, and the lack of predictive biomarkers preventing patients’ stratification to targeted treatments. The lack of predictive tumor biomarkers and the resistance to targeted therapies together with treatment-associated toxicities remain obstacles to therapeutic success of precision medicine. In brief, precision medicine aims to improve diagnostic, therapeutic, and prognostic strategies using large data sets. Incorporation and expansion of real-world data along with implementing of advanced computing and AI capabilities can help predict risk assessment by multidimensional biological and clinical data sets. A better understanding of the disease pathogenesis allows for rapid identification of new and more specific therapeutic interventions. Last but not least, the successful application of precision medicine requires the availability of significant resources such as comprehensive data sets, computational resources, and collaboration among stakeholders (e.g., academia, pharmaceutical industry, healthcare providers, and regulatory agencies).}
